                <note rend="inline" type="source">710.E/169a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1923-01-27T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 27, 1923—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. On January 25, the Chilean Ambassador spoke to the Secretary of the
                    arrangements for the Santiago Conference, and stated that he believed all
                    countries had accepted with the exception of Peru and Mexico. The Ambassador
                    stated that his Government greatly regretted the attitude of Peru as they had
                    reached an agreement for the submission of the Tacna-Arica question to
                    arbitration and that there was now no difficulty between Chile and Peru and that
                    he felt that Peru ought to have viewed the matter in this light and have
                    accepted the invitation. The Ambassador said nothing as to the assertions of
                    Peru that outrages were being committed against Peruvians in Tacna-Arica and the
                    Secretary did not think it best to bring up this question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
